{
    "title": "How to explain your research to a layman when meeting for the first time - Quora",
    "tags": [
        "Research"
    ],
    "response": [
        {
            "author_info": {
                "name": "Jeff Erickson",
                "href": "/profile/Jeff-Erickson"
            },
            "answer_text": "I don\u2019t. Like most mathematicians (if not most researchers), I work off in an obscure corner of the intellectual universe. I do strange things with abstract stuff like binary trees and matrices and recursion and topology that most laymen have no exposure to and don\u2019t care about. Most people don\u2019t even know that university professors do research. Most people would correctly interpret even a cursory description of \u201cmy research\u201d as a flood of meaningless buzzwords, which I\u2019m just throwing at them to make myself sound smart. That\u2019s just rude. I generally talk about more relatable stuff, like teaching, or office politics, or my kids, or travel. Everyone\u2019s had teachers, everyone\u2019s office has politics, everyone has a family, and we\u2019re probably on a plane. Sometimes, especially if the person I\u2019m talking to solves problems for a living (for example: doctor, teacher, electrician, auto mechanic, blacksmith, video editor, portrait artist), we can talk about the problem-solving process. But few people outside the Ivory Tower have dealt with Referee #2 or fought the Notation Demons, and even fewer have ever tried to (or wanted to) understand the role of homology in computing strictly convex drawings of essentially 3-connected graphs on the torus. (See what I mean?) On the extremely rare occasion that someone I\u2019ve just met actually asks about my research (beyond the level of \u201cI design algorithms\u201d), I usually start with something vague like \u201cIt\u2019s pretty abstract. I draw a lot of donuts.\u201d or \u201cDid you ever play Asteroids? Imagine some of the rocks are connected by rubber bands.\u201d ",
