            "author_info": {
                "name": "Jonas Oberhauser",
                "href": "/profile/Jonas-Oberhauser"
            },
            "answer_text": "Hey, have you heard about those airplanes that crashed maybe because of software issues? Yeah, my research field is about preventing that from happening. If they want more detail, I\u2019ll talk to them about toilets, because I think that\u2019s a great way to visualize what I was working on a while back. The story goes like this. Imagine you and a coworker share a toilet booth, but the lock is broken \u2014 you can\u2019t lock the thing, so the only way of knowing if it\u2019s occupied is by opening the door. So you come up with a scheme: whenever you want to go to the toilet, you hang a blanket on the door knob. That way if you see the blanket, you know it\u2019s occupied. As it turns out, software does similar stuff. But now imagine that you wanted to \u201coptimize\u201d your daily life by using a time management system. Like all \u201cgood\u201d time management systems, you begin by using to-do lists. Whenever you have to do something, you put it on the to-do list; that way you can still do it later when it\u2019s convenient, and you can\u2019t forget about doing it. For example, if we have to do the laundry but the shared laundry machine is occupied for the next four hours, it would be inconvenient to wait in front of the machine; it\u2019s better to do other stuff now, and then come back to the laundry machine in four hours. Great, right? Except of course when you enter the toilet, and instead of putting up the blanket immediately, you just put it on the to-do list, because you can still do it later when it\u2019s convenient and you can\u2019t forget about it\u2026 As it turns out, processors do exactly that\u2026 \u201cBut wait!\u201d, you say, \u201cwhy don\u2019t you just figure out when you have to do something immediately, and then not put it on the to-do list?\u201d Ah, yes, and that was exactly what my research was about \u2014 how can we tell easily when we can use the to-do list (which helps us save a lot of time as we can do things when they\u2019re convenient), and when do we have to do things immediately? This is also the level at which I explain it to fellow computer scientists, as any more detailed explanation requires a lot more time. ",
