            "author_info": {
                "name": "Sam Oga",
                "href": "/profile/Sam-Oga"
            },
            "answer_text": "It depends on a lot of factors, how well do you understand your work? do you like talking about it? how much time to you have to impress or depress this layman? is the location suitable? I assume these have already been considered and you have come to the conclusion to share your work. Personally, I love talking about my research, it's flashy and it can pique interest to hear that I use a 5m2 indoor space to grow 5kg of peppermint and raise 3.5kg of fish in 7wks without soil. But sometimes it can become hectic especially to \u2018laymen\u2019 who speaks/majors in a different language. This is why it is very important that you must have a firm grasp on your work, in this way you can explain it using the simplest terms and still retain the uniqueness/specialization. I have once used the flushing system of a toilet (not the most palatable, but it was the best I could come up with at the time) to explain how an aquaponic system works to a tourist. So if I may, a few tips from my experience; Figure out if this layman is really interested in knowing about your work or its just an ice breaker/ conversation bridge. Knowing the difference between the two can help you gauge how much time you have, for instance if you meet at a fair where stuff is displayed and people generally want to have an idea it is not the time to go too deep/technical. In this case, the fun aspect of your work will suffice (this will either invite Ms. layman for more discussion or cultivate a positive mindset about the work hopefully for the future). How \u2018lay\u2019 is the layman? If you\u2019re working on \u2018blackholes and light theories\u2019 or \u2018the difficulty in pronunciation of certain consonants by the Tiv tribe in central Nigeria\u2019 your layman range could be pretty wide. While it is not always possible to ascertain the level of \u2018layness\u2019 until you begin talking it would help a great deal to pick up cues as you progress and adjust accordingly. It would help greatly to have some aids like pictures or everyday analogies to aid you. I always use nature or google up some pictures. Thankfully that works for me, and I understand it may not be plausible in all cases but whenever possible use an aid. Ask follow-up questions so you know if you\u2019re still carrying your layman along. Sometimes we get so engrossed in our research that we bequeath the same level of knowledge to everyone else. Your work must be exciting enough for you in order to sustain the interest of another. Excitement is contagious, I have easily transmitted interest in aquaponics to staff waiting on me in a hotel just by how I spoke about it to a colleague at a conference. I have also been infected with interest in various fields in this same way. I hope this helps, will add more as i remember. Happy talking! ",
