        {
            "author_info": {
                "name": "William Sager",
                "href": "/profile/William-Sager-2"
            },
            "answer_text": "I think about it ahead of time. By layman, I assume that you mean an non-scientist, so I have to leave out technical terms (which takes some thought). And I must keep it simple and short because few people want to hear a lecture. In business, this might be called an \u201celevator pitch\u201d, i.e., a short, 30\u201360 second summary. You need to get across the main idea, so you start with the conclusion and then perhaps tell how you know it. I try to think of visual examples because people respond to things that they can imagine. So try to think of a simple way to explain what you do and to describe it in every day things that can be easily visualized. As I said at the top. This takes some thought, so it\u2019s a good idea to think about your elevator pitch, so it is ready when the opportunity presents itself. ",
